# Intro Game Dev Course

A Unity project built for hands-on introduction to game development.
Each lesson is a self-contained scene that introduces new Unity concepts
through a working example, building progressively toward a complete game.

> **If you're here from class:** open the project in Unity, navigate to
> `Assets/GameDevIntro/`, and start at the scene for your current lesson.
> Each folder contains a scene and a `Readme` asset — open it in the
> Inspector for the lesson's notes and reference links.

---

## What This Project Covers

| Lesson | Topics |
|--------|--------|
| 01 | Unity Editor orientation · GameObjects & components · Inspector · Render order · Play mode |
| 02 | Physics · Rigidbody2D · Colliders · Triggers · Prefabs |
| 03 | Scripting patterns · Object pooling · Time & deltaTime · Coroutines |
| 04 | Scene transitions · Tilemaps · UI Canvas system · 3D basics · Materials & lighting |
| 05 | Audio (AudioSource, AudioMixer) · ScriptableObjects · Settings persistence (PlayerPrefs) · UIElements |
| 06 | Animations · 2d · 3d · Rigging · Skeletons · Avatars |
| 07 | Procedural Generation · RNG · Noise · Physics-Based Motion · Pure C# Classes · Particle System |
| 08 | Genre exploration: platformers · top-down · FPS · RPG combat · dialogue · inventory |
| 09 | *(advanced topics)* |
| 10 | Debugging tools: Profiler · Frame Debugger · Physics Debugger · Input Debugger · breakpoints |
| 11 | Shaders · Shader Graph · VFX Graph |
| 12 | Multiplayer basics · NetworkManager · Input System (PlayerInputManager) |

Lessons assume general programming competency in C# or a comparable language,
but no prior Unity or game development experience.

---

## Getting Started

**Requirements**
- Unity 6 LTS (or the version specified by your instructor)
- Universal Render Pipeline (URP) — included with the project

**Steps**
1. Clone or download this repository.
   - I strongly encourage you to invest a little time to ensure version
   control is working on your projects, if not this tutorial project.
2. Open the project in Unity Hub. (select "Add" -> "Add Project From Disk")
3. In the Project browser, navigate to `Assets/GameDevIntro/`.
4. Open the scene folder for your current lesson (e.g. `01/01.unity`).
5. Select the `Readme` asset in that folder and read it in the Inspector
   before touching anything else.

Each scene is a snapshot of a particular state of the game. Later scenes
build on earlier ones, so if something looks unfamiliar, the earlier lesson
where it was introduced is a good reference point.

---

## Project Structure

```
Assets/
├── GameDevIntro/
│   ├── 01/          # Lesson 01 scene + Readme + Assets
│   ├── 02/          # Lesson 02 scene + Readme + Assets
│   ├── ...
│   └── 12/          # Lesson 12 scene + Readme + Assets
└── ...              # Shared assets (sprites, prefabs, audio, scripts)
```

The in-scene `Readme` assets are the primary documentation for each lesson.
They contain explanations, common pitfalls, and links to the relevant
Unity documentation — read them in the Inspector, not as raw `.asset` files.

---

## A Note on the Readme Assets

Each lesson folder contains a custom `Readme` asset that renders as a
formatted panel in the Unity Inspector. If it's showing up as raw YAML
instead, make sure the `TutorialInfo` scripts in the project are compiled.
Reopening the project or triggering a recompile (adding a blank line to
any `.cs` file and saving) usually resolves this.

---

## Working on Your Own Game

If you get stuck:
- Check the Readme for that lesson's reference links first.
- Search the Unity documentation at [docs.unity3d.com](https://docs.unity3d.com).
- The comments in the tutorial scripts are there to explain decisions, not
  just describe what the code does — they're worth reading.
- There is a tremendous amount of third party resources - articles, videos, forum
  posts, and more - that you are encouraged to take advantage of. You don't have
  to reinvent every wheel you choose to  work with.

